WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.952 --> 00:00:14.960
ALISON EYRING: My story began
on the 14th of May in 2002.

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:18.400
It was exactly 4:50
in the afternoon

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:21.524
and I was working in Shanghai.

00:00:21.524 --> 00:00:23.328
I was there with two
of my colleagues.

00:00:23.328 --> 00:00:25.580
We were working with a client.

00:00:25.580 --> 00:00:28.246
The day was about to end.

00:00:28.246 --> 00:00:29.854
One of my colleagues
came up to me

00:00:29.854 --> 00:00:32.369
with a phone in her hand,
which seemed [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:32.369 --> 00:00:37.540
She said Alison, your family
is trying to reach you.

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:38.930
Immediately, my heart went here.

00:00:38.930 --> 00:00:42.590
Because you always know
that's not a good thing.

00:00:42.590 --> 00:00:44.482
I went outside and
I held the phone

00:00:44.482 --> 00:00:49.180
tightly to my ear to
hear my husband's voice.

00:00:49.180 --> 00:00:52.720
He said to me the thing that
I hope you'll never hear.

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:54.890
He said, Alison,
your mom and dad

00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:57.850
have been in a car accident,
neither who survived.

00:01:00.850 --> 00:01:04.200
That turned my life upside down.

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:07.020
The next 36 hours, I
can hardly remember.

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:10.150
I flew from Shanghai
back to Singapore.

00:01:10.150 --> 00:01:12.172
I went to the United States.

00:01:12.172 --> 00:01:13.835
I met my siblings.

00:01:13.835 --> 00:01:15.900
And I was there for
three weeks with them

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:19.810
before I came back
home to Singapore.

00:01:19.810 --> 00:01:24.570
When I came back to Singapore,
I was so jet lagged, as you are.

00:01:24.570 --> 00:01:27.700
And every morning, I'd wake
up when it was still dark

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:31.960
and I'd crawl out of bed
and I'd go for a walk.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:35.460
I called those my morning
walks because all I could do

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:37.240
was grieve.

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:39.850
Fortunately it was dark
and people passing me

00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:42.050
couldn't see me cry.

00:01:42.050 --> 00:01:47.620
I cried every morning but
I started walking further.

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:50.385
My walks, they became jogs.

00:01:50.385 --> 00:01:54.740
My jogs became trots.

00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:57.190
And then the trotting
became running.

00:01:57.190 --> 00:02:03.150
And I continued to run
until December of that year.

00:02:03.150 --> 00:02:07.450
Now, when December came, I had
a whole new wave of sadness

00:02:07.450 --> 00:02:10.259
happen because Christmas
day was my birthday

00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:11.550
and it was my dad's birthday.

00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:15.330
And so growing up was always so
special because we could always

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:17.280
celebrate that day together.

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:19.260
And I knew that
day, we would never

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:22.560
be able to spend again
celebrating our birthdays.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:25.095
So I'm really not a
cry baby, even though I

00:02:25.095 --> 00:02:27.330
had been crying ever since May.

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:29.400
And I said, that's it.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.714
I got to do something that's
going to give me some hope.

00:02:32.714 --> 00:02:34.130
I had to do something
that's going

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:36.055
to make me work for the future.

00:02:36.055 --> 00:02:39.180
So I thought really long and
hard, what would that be?

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:44.520
And I thought, I'll run
a marathon, as you do.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:47.670
And so I did.

00:02:47.670 --> 00:02:53.950
For the next year, I ran
and I trained and I sweat.

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:57.940
And I ran up till
December when many of you

00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:02.520
may have participated in
the Stan Chart Marathon

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:04.075
in Singapore, of course.

00:03:04.075 --> 00:03:06.640
A December marathon
isn't cool by any stretch

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:07.690
of the imagination.

00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:09.790
And I can still
remember that day.

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:13.560
It was so hot I was sweating
before I even started.

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:16.990
And we had a start off time
at 4:00 in the morning.

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:20.650
I dragged myself through the
42 kilometers of that race.

00:03:20.650 --> 00:03:24.340
And I got to the
end and I cried.

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:29.710
But this time, it was the worst
because it wasn't tears of joy,

00:03:29.710 --> 00:03:33.340
but realizing that all my
running was never going

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:34.840
to bring my mom and dad back.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:46.320
So over the last 15 years, I've
become an endurance athlete.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:52.920
I realized that when I came
to the end of the marathon,

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:54.960
I came to the
realization that I didn't

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:57.630
need to run any more to
heal my broken heart.

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:01.410
I just loved to run and
I wanted to keep running.

00:04:01.410 --> 00:04:03.780
So for the last 15 years,
that's what I've done.

00:04:03.780 --> 00:04:05.220
I became an endurance athlete.

00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:07.470
I've had a great time.

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:11.910
I've run, swum-- you
can say swum, I think--

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:15.840
and ridden a bike
thousands of kilometers.

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:18.560
And I've trained
for and competed

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:20.130
in a 100-kilometer race.

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:24.390
I've done a couple of half
Ironmen, a bunch of marathons,

00:04:24.390 --> 00:04:26.700
half marathons.

00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:27.700
I just loved it.

00:04:27.700 --> 00:04:31.560
And I learned so much
from that experience.

00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:35.310
I've learned so much about,
what is my maximum capacity

00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:36.870
and what are the
capabilities that I

00:04:36.870 --> 00:04:38.910
need to develop for a race?

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:41.760
I've learned a lot about
the importance of pace

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:44.610
and about recovery.

00:04:44.610 --> 00:04:48.400
But most of all, I've learned
an important thing, which

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:52.510
is that if I want to improve
my endurance capacity,

00:04:52.510 --> 00:04:57.040
I have to push myself to go
as fast and far as I can,

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:01.630
but no more until I have
the capacity to sustain it.

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:03.830
And that idea is so important.

00:05:03.830 --> 00:05:06.490
That's what I call
intelligent restraint.

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:07.990
Now, I think it's so important.

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:10.950
I'm going to see if I can work
the technology and show you.

00:05:16.510 --> 00:05:20.110
Those are the pictures
of me doing those sports.

00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:22.360
Here's the definition.

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:25.510
Intelligent restraint
is a growth philosophy.

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:28.660
It's one that says that we
want to go as fast and far

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:34.860
as we can, but no more until
we have the capacity to do so.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:37.380
Now, fortunately
for my family, I

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:39.540
am not a professional athlete.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:44.114
Because if I were, it would not
help us put food on the table.

00:05:44.114 --> 00:05:45.030
What I've been doing--

00:05:45.030 --> 00:05:48.330
I actually have had a day
job for the last 25 years

00:05:48.330 --> 00:05:50.850
working with
companies to help them

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:52.530
solve the people
and organization

00:05:52.530 --> 00:05:54.300
challenges of growth.

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:58.040
And what I see is
that many of us--

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:01.050
and I say us because I
also lead an organization--

00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:03.540
we don't find the right pace.

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:05.940
We don't quite get it right.

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:10.080
And when we experience that,
there's a range of things

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:12.550
that we experience.

00:06:12.550 --> 00:06:16.380
One of them is that we
might see a stall in growth

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:19.040
or we might see
waves of what I call

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:21.810
boom-splat cycles of growth.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:24.930
Then we might see a flurry
of activities because when

00:06:24.930 --> 00:06:26.780
we're on the upside--

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:30.660
I always say growth ignores
a multitude of sins.

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:32.460
So then we're on a
downside, suddenly

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:34.330
we're busy cutting costs.

00:06:34.330 --> 00:06:42.350
Or we're running to roll out
initiatives to stimulate sales,

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:44.000
but we're poorly executing.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.510
We're inconsistently executing.

00:06:46.510 --> 00:06:48.010
Sometimes, with
all those things,

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:51.400
we see employees that are
disengaged and burned out.

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:59.260
Now, I want to make this
more practical for you.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:01.740
And I just want to
ask, could everybody

00:07:01.740 --> 00:07:03.840
just show me your smartphone?

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:06.060
Does everybody have one today?

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:07.170
I'm not disappointed.

00:07:07.170 --> 00:07:09.499
Now I'm, of course, feeling
a little bit exposed here

00:07:09.499 --> 00:07:11.040
because I'm the only
one that doesn't

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:12.140
have a smartphone with me.

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:13.431
You can take your pictures now.

00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:19.090
How many of you have a Samsung?

00:07:19.090 --> 00:07:20.020
Some of you.

00:07:20.020 --> 00:07:22.780
Let me talk a little
bit about the Samsung.

00:07:22.780 --> 00:07:26.200
Now, I got to tell you, when the
Galaxy S7 was coming out-- now,

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:28.750
I'm pretty faithful
to my smartphone

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:30.250
and I like it an awful lot.

00:07:30.250 --> 00:07:33.410
But I was tempted because
it was a good looking phone.

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:38.480
It was nice looking and it
was packed with features.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:39.800
And the price was right.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.810
Samsung had worked very hard.

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:45.590
As a company, it had become
very fast and very progressive

00:07:45.590 --> 00:07:49.970
and quite innovative
in its space.

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:52.520
And when it released
the Galaxy S7,

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:56.360
it did a classic speedy thing
as it looked over its shoulder

00:07:56.360 --> 00:07:59.930
at Apple in a race out.

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:02.090
It went too fast.

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:04.610
And early on, they knew
there was a problem.

00:08:04.610 --> 00:08:06.440
But they were so fast.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.950
They were so unwilling to
stop and to think and learn

00:08:09.950 --> 00:08:12.930
what was going on, that they
failed to understand that they

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:15.020
had created a phone
that they didn't take

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:18.295
into account the requirements
of the battery to not catch on

00:08:18.295 --> 00:08:19.520
fire.

00:08:19.520 --> 00:08:24.050
Going too fast cost them
billions of dollars.

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:28.520
It cost a withdrawal of
a product and huge costs

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:31.480
associated with the brand.

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:34.075
And Samsung's not alone.

00:08:34.075 --> 00:08:40.570
But let's explore another
organization, one I love.

00:08:40.570 --> 00:08:42.220
I grew up--

00:08:42.220 --> 00:08:46.750
Kodak was the king
of photography.

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:49.270
Kodak was this great company.

00:08:49.270 --> 00:08:52.270
We all knew what a
Kodak moment was.

00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:54.641
Does anybody else
remember a Kodak moment?

00:08:54.641 --> 00:08:55.140
Yeah.

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:55.640
OK.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:57.610
This is my age group here.

00:08:57.610 --> 00:08:58.613
I'm liking it.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.030
Kodak was amazingly innovative.

00:09:05.030 --> 00:09:10.820
They developed the
digital camera in 1975.

00:09:10.820 --> 00:09:12.530
But they put it
aside because they

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:15.500
thought it would threaten
their film business.

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:18.050
They weren't willing to take
that step, even when they

00:09:18.050 --> 00:09:20.030
saw the market changing.

00:09:20.030 --> 00:09:23.420
Even when they saw that
photography was changing,

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:26.840
they were unwilling to do what
they thought would threaten

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:29.186
their core business.

00:09:29.186 --> 00:09:31.670
Kodak was encumbered.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:35.570
It was constrained
by its success.

00:09:35.570 --> 00:09:37.440
It had been so
successful that it

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:41.480
was unwilling to push hard
enough and fast enough

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:43.790
and it became irrelevant.

00:09:43.790 --> 00:09:46.100
Eventually, it
declared bankruptcy.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:49.190
It sold off most of its assets.

00:09:49.190 --> 00:09:53.090
I am happy to say it is
coming back in a smaller form.

00:09:53.090 --> 00:09:54.540
It's very focused.

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:57.930
But that'll be another story.

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:04.740
Now, it turns out that
in endurance training,

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:09.240
we have a lot of really
lovely rules of restraint

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:10.950
that can help us.

00:10:10.950 --> 00:10:14.890
And I've always found them
to be particularly helpful.

00:10:14.890 --> 00:10:17.350
What I find-- and I'll
give you an example.

00:10:17.350 --> 00:10:19.670
For instance, let's
say you're running.

00:10:19.670 --> 00:10:22.090
You don't want to increase
your mileage more than 10%

00:10:22.090 --> 00:10:23.140
in a week.

00:10:23.140 --> 00:10:25.690
Or you don't want
to increase, maybe,

00:10:25.690 --> 00:10:26.890
the length of a long run.

00:10:26.890 --> 00:10:30.150
Or maybe before a triathlon--

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:33.310
not a triathlon, a longer
distance, like a marathon,

00:10:33.310 --> 00:10:34.360
you start to taper.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:36.460
So there's these
really nice easy rules

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:39.160
of thumb that could help
guide the ramping up

00:10:39.160 --> 00:10:41.520
and the ramping down of the
volume of your training.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:42.610
I love those rules.

00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:44.200
They're so simple to apply.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:47.070
But we don't really have those
rules of restraint in business.

00:10:47.070 --> 00:10:48.940
Now, don't get me
wrong, business

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:51.435
is full of rules of
restraint, right?

00:10:51.435 --> 00:10:53.950
There are things
like don't divulge

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:55.750
confidential information.

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:57.880
Don't give anyone your password.

00:10:57.880 --> 00:11:02.470
Don't give information
in a negotiation.

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:04.210
Don't have an
inappropriate relationship

00:11:04.210 --> 00:11:06.050
with your subordinates.

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:10.250
They keep us from doing bad
things, which is a good thing.

00:11:10.250 --> 00:11:12.820
But they don't show
us how to grow.

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:17.230
They don't show us how
we can push our capacity

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:21.340
for growth, and at the same
time, perform as a business.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:25.060
I want to share with you three
rules of intelligent restraint

00:11:25.060 --> 00:11:28.330
that I think are fabulous
and easy to apply.

00:11:28.330 --> 00:11:31.210
And my hope for you is
that, tomorrow, you'll

00:11:31.210 --> 00:11:32.860
start thinking about,
well, how can I

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:35.070
put these to work for myself?

00:11:35.070 --> 00:11:37.310
Now, there's three.

00:11:37.310 --> 00:11:41.890
The first is focus
overrules vision.

00:11:41.890 --> 00:11:44.320
The second, teams
beat strengths.

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:47.374
And the third is
exert, then recover.

00:11:47.374 --> 00:11:49.540
And what I'd like to do is
spend the rest of my time

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:53.320
with you talking through
those three rules.

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:57.700
Let me focus on the first
one, focus overrules vision.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:59.710
Now, before I
moved to Singapore,

00:11:59.710 --> 00:12:01.930
I lived in Dallas, Texas.

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:05.080
And in December,
sometime in the '90s,

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:08.440
I can remember going to
see the Dallas marathon.

00:12:08.440 --> 00:12:10.820
And James and I-- my husband--

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:13.120
he and I went to see
it with our friends.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:16.420
And Harry and I stood at
the end, at the finish line.

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:19.510
Meanwhile, James and Christine
sat inside a nice warm cafe

00:12:19.510 --> 00:12:21.760
nearby and ate pancakes.

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:24.370
Well, Harry and I were
so excited at the end,

00:12:24.370 --> 00:12:26.860
watching and cheering people on.

00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:29.290
Men, and women, and young
people and old people,

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:31.390
and fat people and
skinny people--

00:12:31.390 --> 00:12:33.390
everyone was crossing
the finish line.

00:12:33.390 --> 00:12:35.260
And we were so excited.

00:12:35.260 --> 00:12:40.330
At one point, an athlete with
one leg and with crutches

00:12:40.330 --> 00:12:42.430
crossed the finish line.

00:12:42.430 --> 00:12:44.800
We were so inspired.

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:47.800
Harry and I looked at
each other so excited

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.140
because that man inspired us.

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:53.080
And we looked at each other
and, with complete earnestness,

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:57.870
we shook hands and said we're
going to run a marathon.

00:12:57.870 --> 00:12:59.940
Well, the years went
by and the vision

00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:02.280
faded, as did the passion.

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:08.490
Life intervened and it never
brought us to the marathon.

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:12.240
What brought me to the marathon,
eventually, wasn't the vision.

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:14.430
It was focus.

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:15.990
Now, my first marathon--

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:19.820
I had the holy focus of hope.

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:21.660
I mean, who wouldn't?

00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:25.140
But after that, actually,
what drove me, the focus,

00:13:25.140 --> 00:13:26.850
was actually a lot simpler.

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:30.540
I simply knew what the
next race would be.

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:33.060
Once I knew what the
next race would be,

00:13:33.060 --> 00:13:35.130
I could have goals for
that race and say, well,

00:13:35.130 --> 00:13:37.560
what is it actually
that I want to do?

00:13:37.560 --> 00:13:40.890
And then I'd say, now, what's
it going to take to succeed?

00:13:40.890 --> 00:13:44.130
Those three things
helped me get focus.

00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:47.520
Once I had focus, I
could line up my life.

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:50.730
I could allocate
time and resources.

00:13:50.730 --> 00:13:52.050
Since I'm a busy person--

00:13:52.050 --> 00:13:56.130
I got a family, I work, I do
all of this stuff on the side--

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:57.990
I'd have to say no
to certain things.

00:13:57.990 --> 00:14:01.020
And I'd have to line up
resources that would allow me

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:02.690
to allocate the time to train.

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:05.130
Because you can't really
cheat races like that.

00:14:05.130 --> 00:14:06.880
You can cheat a half marathon.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:09.450
You can't cheat 100k.

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:12.360
And so you really
have to change things.

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:15.420
You have to create routines.

00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:20.010
So once I had the focus, I was
able to create a discipline

00:14:20.010 --> 00:14:22.350
that allowed me to finish.

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:24.450
What I see often
in the work that we

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:27.950
do in organizations
is sometimes,

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:29.790
there's a fuzzy vision.

00:14:29.790 --> 00:14:32.880
And sometimes, there's a bit
of a vision of growth, which

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:35.520
usually translates to
something like, we're

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:38.730
going to double our
sales at three years

00:14:38.730 --> 00:14:43.890
or we want x percent improvement
in EBITDA over the next three

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:45.270
years.

00:14:45.270 --> 00:14:48.120
So often, we just have
a numerical target.

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:51.480
What I see is that so many
leaders understand the race

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:53.820
they're in today,
but they don't know

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:56.340
what that next race will be.

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:58.550
If we don't know
that next race, we

00:14:58.550 --> 00:15:01.410
can't know what success looks
like when we achieve it,

00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:04.110
and we can't decide
what it takes to win.

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:12.190
The leaders who really get it
right, that's what they do.

00:15:12.190 --> 00:15:14.620
They create incredible focus.

00:15:14.620 --> 00:15:17.740
Not only focus for themselves,
but focus with others

00:15:17.740 --> 00:15:18.970
in the organization.

00:15:18.970 --> 00:15:22.390
They build a critical mass
that understands that.

00:15:22.390 --> 00:15:26.320
And then they work very hard
to line up the resources needed

00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:28.330
in order to win.

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:31.180
I will say that in the work
that we do with growth leaders,

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:34.180
we sometimes find that
they're not very popular.

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:36.850
Because sometimes
it's easy to say yes.

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:38.950
It's hard to say no.

00:15:38.950 --> 00:15:40.510
It's easy to take resources.

00:15:40.510 --> 00:15:42.370
It's hard to give them up.

00:15:42.370 --> 00:15:45.340
So it's very challenging
for growth leaders

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:47.650
to not only create
focus, but also

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:50.170
to create real
alignment that means

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:54.890
that we allocate resources
to what really matters.

00:15:54.890 --> 00:15:58.450
So I leave you with a thought
that while vision can get you

00:15:58.450 --> 00:16:01.230
to the race, it's actually
focus that gets you

00:16:01.230 --> 00:16:03.420
across the finish line.

00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:10.710
Now, second rule is
routines beat strengths.

00:16:10.710 --> 00:16:14.960
Now, when I first
started running,

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:18.260
I fell in love with it.

00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:20.272
I think it was because
I read this great book.

00:16:20.272 --> 00:16:21.980
It was called Running
the Spiritual Path.

00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:25.700
And it basically taught me about
how to do running meditation.

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:28.190
And I would go out--

00:16:28.190 --> 00:16:31.490
nothing made me happier
than to go out at about 6:00

00:16:31.490 --> 00:16:35.130
in the morning and
run on trails all day.

00:16:35.130 --> 00:16:37.850
This didn't make my family
very happy, by the way.

00:16:37.850 --> 00:16:42.050
But to be breathing, and
meditating, and running,

00:16:42.050 --> 00:16:44.010
I just absolutely loved it.

00:16:44.010 --> 00:16:47.480
Now, I was pretty slow,
but that didn't bother me

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:51.110
because I knew in my heart
that this was my strength.

00:16:51.110 --> 00:16:55.220
In fact, I even read books
that ridiculed people like me.

00:16:55.220 --> 00:16:58.580
And they called it LSD,
Long Slow Distance.

00:16:58.580 --> 00:17:00.710
And I said, that doesn't matter.

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:01.820
I'm a donkey.

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:02.890
That's what I'd say.

00:17:02.890 --> 00:17:05.730
Not an ass, a donkey.

00:17:05.730 --> 00:17:07.700
And so it served me well.

00:17:07.700 --> 00:17:11.740
I could run very
far, very slowly.

00:17:11.740 --> 00:17:16.310
But one day, at the end of a
40k run, I was coming back.

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:18.140
I was in the jungle.

00:17:18.140 --> 00:17:21.800
And it was in a
very narrow trail.

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:24.770
And there was this
very large male monkey

00:17:24.770 --> 00:17:26.359
sitting in front of me.

00:17:26.359 --> 00:17:29.120
Now, I was a little
smelly at this point

00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:31.940
because I had been running for
a really long time with a camel

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:33.500
pack and lots of food in it.

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:36.470
And I must have smelled
like eau de banana.

00:17:36.470 --> 00:17:39.295
And as I came up to
that monkey, he shrieked

00:17:39.295 --> 00:17:40.700
and he came towards me.

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:43.220
And I shrieked and I ran
in the other direction.

00:17:43.220 --> 00:17:45.380
I took off like a gazelle.

00:17:45.380 --> 00:17:48.320
As I sprinted, I felt
the dagger of his teeth

00:17:48.320 --> 00:17:49.760
into the back of my calf.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:50.930
I screeched.

00:17:50.930 --> 00:17:52.400
I looked back.

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:54.380
There was no monkey.

00:17:54.380 --> 00:17:59.180
In my haste to escape, in
my sprint of a gazelle,

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:01.930
I tore my calf.

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:04.260
I learned a very
important lesson.

00:18:04.260 --> 00:18:06.310
You can't run like
a gazelle when

00:18:06.310 --> 00:18:08.073
you've trained like a donkey.

00:18:08.073 --> 00:18:10.538
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:16.160
I thought I had this strength.

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:18.210
It turned out not
to be a strength.

00:18:18.210 --> 00:18:23.610
And what I learned is that
my strength, it limited me.

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:24.570
But we're the same way.

00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:26.700
Think of how many
organizations--

00:18:26.700 --> 00:18:29.940
we limit ourselves from
changing because we

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:32.900
want to rely on who we are
and what's made us successful.

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:40.840
When I changed tack, I
recovered from my torn calf,

00:18:40.840 --> 00:18:42.940
I decided I wanted
a new challenge.

00:18:42.940 --> 00:18:44.680
I would do triathlons.

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:46.760
That was much easier on my body.

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:49.930
And so I decided to
do a half Ironman.

00:18:49.930 --> 00:18:52.210
So since I didn't
know what to do,

00:18:52.210 --> 00:18:55.240
I hired a sports coach, which
I'm very thankful I did.

00:18:55.240 --> 00:18:58.180
And I worked with a man named
Scott Molina, who himself is

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:00.940
an Ironman athlete and a coach.

00:19:00.940 --> 00:19:02.650
And he worked with
me and I learned

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:05.020
something that was profound.

00:19:05.020 --> 00:19:09.130
And it was that if I wanted to
improve the capacity of my body

00:19:09.130 --> 00:19:12.250
to go further and faster,
what I needed to do

00:19:12.250 --> 00:19:16.100
was implement progressively
challenging routines.

00:19:16.100 --> 00:19:17.860
Our bodies are smart.

00:19:17.860 --> 00:19:23.710
Like any system, if we don't
push them, they stay the same.

00:19:23.710 --> 00:19:27.040
In fact, even going out and
having a really tough workout

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:28.390
doesn't make any difference.

00:19:28.390 --> 00:19:29.587
It just keeps coming back.

00:19:29.587 --> 00:19:31.420
It's one of the reasons
why you should never

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:34.551
restrict your calories too much
because your body doesn't just

00:19:34.551 --> 00:19:35.050
lose weight.

00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:37.870
It says, oh no, you're
starving, and it suddenly

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:39.370
becomes very efficient.

00:19:39.370 --> 00:19:41.260
Our bodies are very smart.

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:44.020
What I learned from these
progressively challenging

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:47.680
routines was that
it was the routine

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:50.560
and the ongoing
challenge that sparked

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:54.385
the development of my capacity.

00:19:54.385 --> 00:19:55.760
I think this is
really important.

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:58.450
There's an awful lot of
people in this room that are

00:19:58.450 --> 00:20:01.330
in fields of human development.

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:04.320
And we've known for two
decades that experience

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:05.590
is a great teacher.

00:20:05.590 --> 00:20:09.254
And we know that challenge
in experience develops.

00:20:09.254 --> 00:20:11.420
But I want you just to go
away and think about that.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:13.370
It's not just challenge.

00:20:13.370 --> 00:20:16.840
It's progressively
challenging routines.

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:18.580
That changes systems.

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:19.850
That's what changes us.

00:20:19.850 --> 00:20:23.070
It's not just a
random challenge.

00:20:23.070 --> 00:20:29.260
Now, I want to give you an
example of an organization

00:20:29.260 --> 00:20:33.320
that I think did a great job
with introducing a routine,

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:35.950
just to make this practical.

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:37.686
This is a company--

00:20:37.686 --> 00:20:39.165
I'll call it ArtCo.

00:20:39.165 --> 00:20:42.730
It's a marketplace
or platform for arts

00:20:42.730 --> 00:20:45.700
and designed products for homes.

00:20:45.700 --> 00:20:50.170
And ArtCo has been
very successful.

00:20:50.170 --> 00:20:54.290
And it was growing so
fast that-- when you're

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:55.730
in a very high
growth environment,

00:20:55.730 --> 00:20:57.730
it's very challenging
because you start your job

00:20:57.730 --> 00:20:59.210
and, suddenly, it's changing.

00:20:59.210 --> 00:21:01.600
So you have to be
changing very fast.

00:21:01.600 --> 00:21:03.830
And the volume of work
is constantly changing.

00:21:03.830 --> 00:21:06.220
There's a lot of newness,
a lot of challenge.

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:10.210
And one of the things that ArtCo
decided that they wanted to do

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:14.290
was to find a way to
help themselves scale.

00:21:14.290 --> 00:21:17.910
So they introduced a routine
they call scaling day.

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:21.650
And as it sounds, scaling
day happened once a month.

00:21:21.650 --> 00:21:24.430
And it started-- they'd
pick a little problem.

00:21:24.430 --> 00:21:27.520
They would pick processes
or work activities

00:21:27.520 --> 00:21:32.290
that they knew needed to scale,
in order to sustain growth.

00:21:32.290 --> 00:21:37.140
And they had this
fabulous office.

00:21:37.140 --> 00:21:39.640
In the middle, they
have a glass room.

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:42.320
Many of us have been
involved in activities

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:43.770
of documenting processes.

00:21:43.770 --> 00:21:46.230
And usually, we sit
around and we have Word

00:21:46.230 --> 00:21:48.160
documents and Google documents.

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:50.470
And we're documenting
lots of details

00:21:50.470 --> 00:21:52.900
and no one cares about what
we write and no one ever

00:21:52.900 --> 00:21:53.870
looks at it.

00:21:53.870 --> 00:21:57.100
But what ArtCo did was they
made it part of their culture.

00:21:57.100 --> 00:21:59.440
Scaling day was
something that people

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:00.970
wanted to be a part
of because they

00:22:00.970 --> 00:22:02.930
knew it was part of the future.

00:22:02.930 --> 00:22:04.480
And so people volunteered.

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:05.470
They gave their time.

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:09.550
They used it to be able
to scale for growth.

00:22:09.550 --> 00:22:11.740
Now, in my book,
Pacing for Growth,

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:13.960
which I'm so excited
for you all to read,

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:16.000
you'll find a lot of
examples of routines

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:20.410
that you can use and implement
to build organization, team,

00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:24.340
leader capabilities that
you need for the future.

00:22:24.340 --> 00:22:28.060
The beauty of a routine
is that the right routine

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:31.550
helps you build the capabilities
that you need for the future

00:22:31.550 --> 00:22:35.178
and it also helps
you conserve energy.

00:22:35.178 --> 00:22:39.440
Now, let me talk
about the last one.

00:22:39.440 --> 00:22:41.370
Exert and then recover.

00:22:41.370 --> 00:22:42.845
It's a little bit different.

00:22:42.845 --> 00:22:49.040
And I have to start with my
own reflection a very important

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:51.950
recovery moment.

00:22:51.950 --> 00:22:54.820
In that first half
Ironman that I did--

00:22:54.820 --> 00:22:57.360
that was the hardest
race I'd ever done.

00:22:57.360 --> 00:22:59.000
It took me over seven hours.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:00.020
And I came back.

00:23:00.020 --> 00:23:01.760
I was so tired.

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:04.250
I remember my husband
and girls, they kind of

00:23:04.250 --> 00:23:07.130
scraped me off the floor
and they put me in the car

00:23:07.130 --> 00:23:09.080
and they took me home.

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:10.910
James, in the most
loving way, had

00:23:10.910 --> 00:23:13.630
filled the bathtub full of ice.

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:16.100
He's just a man
after my own heart,

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:18.560
which is what I would do
after a really long run

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:20.750
because it would lower
my body temperature

00:23:20.750 --> 00:23:23.130
and reduce inflammation.

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:24.510
My daughters were so sweet.

00:23:24.510 --> 00:23:26.700
They created a
little spa for me.

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:29.010
And I believe that they
were giving me massages.

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:31.020
But I fell asleep so
quickly I don't even

00:23:31.020 --> 00:23:32.490
remember what happened.

00:23:32.490 --> 00:23:35.790
I woke up, consumed massive
amounts of carbohydrates,

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:39.000
fell asleep, and felt
much better the next day.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.780
Now, that's recovery.

00:23:41.780 --> 00:23:45.100
Actually, that's
called passive recovery

00:23:45.100 --> 00:23:48.460
because passive
recovery is when we rest

00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:50.020
and we recharge our battery.

00:23:50.020 --> 00:23:52.240
And we all need that, right?

00:23:52.240 --> 00:23:54.250
I think that's why
a lot of us are

00:23:54.250 --> 00:23:56.890
happy that Friday is tomorrow.

00:23:56.890 --> 00:23:59.350
So passive recovery
is really important.

00:23:59.350 --> 00:24:02.170
It allows us to recharge.

00:24:02.170 --> 00:24:04.270
But there's another
kind of a recovery

00:24:04.270 --> 00:24:05.540
that's equally important.

00:24:05.540 --> 00:24:07.720
And that's called
active recovery.

00:24:07.720 --> 00:24:11.200
And at work, we tend to
think, well, I'm working

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:12.550
or I'm not working.

00:24:12.550 --> 00:24:14.950
And with active
recovery, what we'll do

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:19.330
is we have a recovery
workout where we go slower.

00:24:19.330 --> 00:24:20.600
Heart rate is slower.

00:24:20.600 --> 00:24:22.505
It's easier on our body.

00:24:22.505 --> 00:24:25.090
And it not only
helps us recover,

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:26.800
but it helps condition.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:30.880
And it helps teach
our body how to exert.

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:33.760
And that's an important
aspect of the relationship

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:35.249
between exertion and recovery

00:24:35.249 --> 00:24:36.040
It's kind of funny.

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:38.890
It's not the exertion
that helps us improve.

00:24:38.890 --> 00:24:41.590
It's actually the
recovery, which I always

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:43.250
find so interesting.

00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:46.910
I remember, I think
Troy told me a story.

00:24:46.910 --> 00:24:48.640
Troy will be on our panel.

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:52.000
He said that when the
players are playing the game,

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.740
it's too late to coach.

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:57.820
And so one of the things
that we have to do

00:24:57.820 --> 00:25:01.690
is to learn how to exert with
the right level of exertion,

00:25:01.690 --> 00:25:03.220
and then to properly recover--

00:25:03.220 --> 00:25:05.530
because those two
go hand-in-hand.

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:08.770
One of the things about
exertion is that often, we

00:25:08.770 --> 00:25:11.170
just mindlessly exert.

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:14.870
We're like hamsters in a cage
and we're addicted to action.

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:16.420
We're just doing, doing, doing.

00:25:16.420 --> 00:25:18.160
And we're not
thinking about, what's

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:20.640
the purpose of my exertion?

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:23.620
In training, we'll
have really high levels

00:25:23.620 --> 00:25:26.500
where we're going all
out, just pushing up

00:25:26.500 --> 00:25:28.000
the capacity of our heart.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:29.269
Sometimes, we do race pace.

00:25:29.269 --> 00:25:30.310
And race pace is helpful.

00:25:30.310 --> 00:25:33.130
It helps us know what
it feels like when

00:25:33.130 --> 00:25:34.480
we're going to be in the race.

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:38.500
There's other times where it's
just a little bit lower, where

00:25:38.500 --> 00:25:41.500
we're really pushing
our aerobic capacity

00:25:41.500 --> 00:25:43.480
and we're building our strength.

00:25:43.480 --> 00:25:45.880
And then we have our
recovery workouts.

00:25:45.880 --> 00:25:48.010
So part of what we have
to do as leaders is

00:25:48.010 --> 00:25:53.260
learn to exert on what matters
and at the right level.

00:25:53.260 --> 00:25:56.980
And we need to learn to balance
the right kind of recovery

00:25:56.980 --> 00:25:57.960
with that.

00:25:57.960 --> 00:26:02.470
What I see with the
leaders that I work with--

00:26:02.470 --> 00:26:07.820
leaders of growth face constant
pressure because, on one hand,

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:10.600
we want to build
capabilities for the future.

00:26:10.600 --> 00:26:15.130
At the same time, we have
to execute today's business.

00:26:15.130 --> 00:26:18.940
And if we can't execute today's
business, if we can't perform,

00:26:18.940 --> 00:26:21.070
there will be no future.

00:26:21.070 --> 00:26:22.620
So really, we have to do both.

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:24.940
We have to perform
today and we have

00:26:24.940 --> 00:26:26.810
to transform for the future.

00:26:26.810 --> 00:26:29.380
And we have to learn how to do
these things without killing

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:30.430
people.

00:26:30.430 --> 00:26:33.580
