00:39:35.750 --> 00:39:38.700
we talk about the principle
of specificity of training.

00:39:38.700 --> 00:39:41.910
You have to understand
what the specific demands

00:39:41.910 --> 00:39:45.190
of the athletic performance
are and you train for those.

00:39:45.190 --> 00:39:50.256
You focus on the 97%,
rather than the 3%.

00:39:50.256 --> 00:39:53.160
We talk about the principles
of load and recovery

00:39:53.160 --> 00:39:57.300
because the adaptation
actually happens in that time

00:39:57.300 --> 00:40:03.720
away from the exertion when
the body reflects and adapts.

00:40:03.720 --> 00:40:07.680
Principles of progressive
overload, that you constantly

00:40:07.680 --> 00:40:08.430
stress the system.

00:40:08.430 --> 00:40:11.010
Because from a
coaching standpoint,

00:40:11.010 --> 00:40:13.722
all the advances
happen at the margin.

00:40:13.722 --> 00:40:15.430
They don't happen
through under-training.

00:40:15.430 --> 00:40:18.760
And they absolutely don't
happen through overtraining.

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:22.535
And in the endurance world, as
Alison and I have talked about,

00:40:22.535 --> 00:40:25.700
there are three or four
different critical margins.

00:40:25.700 --> 00:40:28.200
There's submaximal margins.

00:40:28.200 --> 00:40:31.330
There's margins that
we talk about called

00:40:31.330 --> 00:40:34.950
the anaerobic threshold, which
is that level that you can

00:40:34.950 --> 00:40:38.190
basically maintain for an
extended period of time

00:40:38.190 --> 00:40:41.200
without accumulating fatigue.

00:40:41.200 --> 00:40:42.966
That's a really
critical threshold.

00:40:42.966 --> 00:40:44.460
It's highly trainable.

00:40:44.460 --> 00:40:47.040
You go beyond, you
stress the system where

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:49.080
there's a risk of breakdown.

00:40:49.080 --> 00:40:52.710
And then there are super maximal
thresholds, which you probably

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:57.900
need, at times, to bump to
so you can expect that pace.

00:40:57.900 --> 00:41:01.260
You can train for those
changes in the market, changes

00:41:01.260 --> 00:41:02.470
in the pace.

00:41:02.470 --> 00:41:05.280
But you know you can't
sustain them for long,

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:08.100
so you throttle back
down and regroup.

00:41:08.100 --> 00:41:11.490
So I'm reading this going,
geez, this book is--

00:41:11.490 --> 00:41:14.050
number one, it makes
me feel smart because I

00:41:14.050 --> 00:41:16.680
see my track coaching could
actually, probably, be

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:19.200
more than just with what we do.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:20.490
But it works for everybody.

00:41:20.490 --> 00:41:22.020
It's not principles
that are only

00:41:22.020 --> 00:41:24.060
applied at the Olympic level.

00:41:24.060 --> 00:41:28.570
They're also with-- they're
responses throughout all

00:41:28.570 --> 00:41:29.980
of endurance training.

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:32.490
ALISON EYRING: One thing
I was going to add--

00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:36.150
often, organizations really
struggle to think about,

00:41:36.150 --> 00:41:38.490
what is their maximum capacity?

00:41:38.490 --> 00:41:39.550
We understand today.

00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:41.400
But it's hard to
imagine, how are we

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:43.270
going to be changed tomorrow?

00:41:43.270 --> 00:41:46.770
And one of the stories I told in
the book that I loved was about

00:41:46.770 --> 00:41:51.480
how all the experts used to say
the four-minute mile cannot be

00:41:51.480 --> 00:41:52.350
broken.

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:52.890
Right?

00:41:52.890 --> 00:41:54.360
It was just not going to happen.

00:41:54.360 --> 00:41:58.680
And it took a young
doctor in the UK

00:41:58.680 --> 00:42:01.080
who trained for three
months and then broke it.

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:03.520
And then the record's been
broken 17 times since.

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:05.870
And so I think that
we see that in sport.

00:42:05.870 --> 00:42:08.380
That we often have
that idea about, well,

00:42:08.380 --> 00:42:09.840
what's the best I can be?

00:42:09.840 --> 00:42:11.572
But then in fact, it's not true.

00:42:11.572 --> 00:42:12.780
TROY ENGLE: There have been--

00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:14.550
Roger Bannister broke
the four minute mile.

00:42:14.550 --> 00:42:16.174
And they said it
could never be broken.

00:42:16.174 --> 00:42:18.140
And there have now
been over 400 people.

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:22.990
So we just recalibrate.

00:42:22.990 --> 00:42:25.290
And the earlier point
about ethical decisions.

00:42:25.290 --> 00:42:27.610
I think, clearly
within our world,

00:42:27.610 --> 00:42:29.870
ethics is a huge issue in sport.

00:42:29.870 --> 00:42:31.652
Drugs in sport are
a major problem.

00:42:31.652 --> 00:42:33.420
The thing that most
people don't realize

00:42:33.420 --> 00:42:35.980
is that the most common drugs--

00:42:35.980 --> 00:42:37.460
they don't make you faster.

00:42:37.460 --> 00:42:40.545
What they allow you
to do is work more.

00:42:40.545 --> 00:42:45.780
They reinforce that thought
that more is always better.

00:42:45.780 --> 00:42:49.820
But the reality is it's
not no pain no gain.

00:42:49.820 --> 00:42:53.690
It's no brain, lots
of pain, or something.

00:42:53.690 --> 00:42:56.580
You really have to figure out
what the capacity is and it's

00:42:56.580 --> 00:42:58.210
there for a reason.

00:42:58.210 --> 00:43:00.080
DARRYL DICKENS: On
maximum capacity,

00:43:00.080 --> 00:43:01.690
